Breakfast and Lunch Program For TOTAL REMOTE Learning Students~
Maritime Middle and High School Parents, if your child is learning remotely from home (total remote learning, 5 days a week) he/she is eligible for breakfast and lunch pick up. Your child must be signed up prior to pick up. Please contact our Food Service Director, Ms. Robin, at 842-6289,ext.3365. Breakfast and lunch will be provided for the full week with 2 pickup days from our Middle School only, 102 Buffum St. 14210. Pick up days will be Mon and Thursday between 9 am-11am. Monday pickup will provide breakfast and lunch through Wednesday. Thursday pickup will provide breakfast and lunch through Friday. Your child must be enrolled as a student at Maritime Middle or High School in order to participate.

post_text:
Here is your Saturday morning fact, 2 for 1 today...
1) Bob Ross, the famous television painter, passed away 25 years ago (on July 4th, 1995).

2) Bob Ross was also an Air Force veteran.

Have a great weekend.
shared_text:
Veterans Benefits Administration (VBA), U.S. Department of Veterans Affairs
July 11 at 10:00 AM ·

This year marks the 25th anniversary of the passing of Robert ‘Bob’ Ross, U.S. Air Force Veteran, painter, and host of “The Joy of Painting” where his signature positivity and soft-spoken demeanor continues to endear him to millions of fans today.

After enlisting at the age of 18, Ross was stationed at Eielson United States Air Force Base in Alaska which would eventually serve as the inspiration behind the landscapes he would become known for. Ross served 20 years with the Air Force, including some years as a drill sergeant, before retiring at the rank of Master Sergeant in 1981.

He would go on to create and host his popular TV series where he taught techniques for landscape oil painting from 1984 to 1994. We honor the service and cultural contributions of Bob Ross.

post_text: It doesn't seem right not launching boats, but what about this year has been right???
shared_text:
Buffalo Maritime Center is with Ron Kowalewski at Buffalo Maritime Center.
June 11 at 4:56 PM · Buffalo, NY ·

If this were any other year, we would have been celebrating the hard work and dedication of our Buffalo students in our Hand-to-Hand program with our annual Spring Launch at #HoytLake. Unfortunately, our students won’t get to put their boats in the water this spring, but the Hand-to-Hand program is not just the Spring Launch. It is the process along the way that brings mentors together with students so that we all continue to learn.

We’re asking you to please take the time to see this year’s students of BMC’s Hand-to-Hand Program in action. Help us celebrate them and congratulate the work they’ve done and will continue to do! Thanks to students of #WNYMaritimeCharterSchool, #RiversideAcademy, #AcademySchool, #StMarysSchoolfortheDeaf and, of course, our #volunteer #mentors ! We miss you guys and can’t wait to see you again in the Fall!

post_text: A follow up to our Maritime Day post from yesterday. There are lots of options out...
shared_text:
Interlake Steamship Company
May 22 at 12:15 PM ·

Alex Althaus is no ordinary seaman; although technically she is.

An OS deckhand in her third season sailing with Interlake, she says she does whatever it takes to “hang with the boys on deck” and makes whatever improvements or sacrifices she needs to to reach her goals working on the ships.

“There aren’t many females that have it in them to do what I do in a male-dominated industry,” says the 29-year-old Findlay, Ohio native.

She says one of the most interesting aspects about being a merchant mariner is that as you sail away from land, it’s really an invisible yet essential industry.

“The country simply wouldn’t progress without these materials we haul, and that’s something to be proud of despite all of the challenges of being underway and out on the Lakes,” she says. “If you invest in Interlake, it will be returned. My job absolutely has challenges, leaving everything I know and work hard for is difficult but with great risk comes great reward.”

#NationalMaritimeDay

post_text:
Today is National Maritime Day.

National Maritime Day was first declared by Congress in 1933 to commemorate the American steamship Savannah’s voyage across the Atlantic, quietly sparking a new age of maritime travel and transport. With WWII, the holiday took on special significance when around 250,000 members of United States Merchant Marine participated in transporting necessary supplies and services to troops abroad, all while suffering an extraordinarily high casualty rate. According to the Maritime Administration, more than 6,700 American merchant mariners lost their lives in the War, with hundreds being detained as prisoners of war and more than 800 U.S. merchant ships being sunk or damaged.

Have a great day and please stay safe and healthy!

U.S. Celebrates National Maritime Day
text:
Today is National Maritime Day.

National Maritime Day was first declared by Congress in 1933 to commemorate the American steamship Savannah’s voyage across the Atlantic, quietly sparking a new age of maritime travel and transport. With WWII, the holiday took on special significance when around 250,000 members of United States Merchant Marine participated in transporting necessary supplies and services to troops abroad, all while suffering an extraordinarily high casualty rate. According to the Maritime Administration, more than 6,700 American merchant mariners lost their lives in the War, with hundreds being detained as prisoners of war and more than 800 U.S. merchant ships being sunk or damaged.

Have a great day and please stay safe and healthy!

GCAPTAIN.COM
U.S. Celebrates National Maritime Day

Coronavirus update 5/1/2020 -
Hello Maritime Families,
With the Governor's latest update closing New York schools for the rest of the year we want to let you know that we are working hard to develop plans on finishing up the school year and will release details early next week.

While this year ended in a way none of us could have ever imagined, now is the time to take full advantage of the opportunity to finish and graduate or move up to the next grade. Our teachers are working diligently to ensure all students can complete the assignments given the current situations and are being very generous in their grading. If students are not passing their online assignments, there is a chance they will not move on to the next grade or graduate. Students are fully expected to continue their online classwork and participate, log in to Google Classroom or Schoology on a daily basis, stay in touch with their teachers, and reach out for help as soon as they need it.

Thank you, stay home, stay safe, and stay healthy. http://edl.io/n1220755

post_text:
Since we are the WNY MARITIME Charter School.... Here's to the women that work in the Maritime sector.

Shipping has historically been a male-dominated industry and that tradition runs long and deep. However, through its global programme on the Integration of Women in the Maritime Sector, IMO is making a concerted effort to help the industry move on from that tradition and to help women achieve a representation within it that is more in keeping with twenty-first century expectations.

National organizations such as WIMO’s brings together women working in operations roles within the maritime industry. WIMO’s provides a networking environment, and also gives women in maritime operations opportunities for additional training and volunteer work.

#internationalwomensday #maritime #womenleaders #WomenAtSea #WIMO #WomeninMaritimeOperations

MARITIMECYPRUS.COM

post_text:
This past weekend, there was a bustle of activity at the school. In addition to the Basketball and Academic teams in action, we participated in a Science Olympiad event. 10 cadets competed in the regional competition this past weekend at Buffalo State College. The team competed in 20 events, facing off against nearly 40 area teams. Our team earned a total of 4 medals, finishing in 7th place for the Boomilever and Geologic Mapping events. The team also received an honorable mention for our gravity powered vehicle.

We also held another open house at our Middle School location and advertised the school to prospective cadets and/or candidates.

It was a great weekend to be part of MARITIME!

Conorozzo Memorial Scholarship Fund - Mr. Angelo Conorozzo was one of the five founding members of Maritime and served from 2008 to 2016 as President of the school’s Board of Trustees. As a career educator, Mr. Conorozzo understood and strongly supported the mission of Maritime. Over the last three years, scholarships in the amount of $14,000 have been awarded to eight graduating cadets. Would you please help us raise even more this year to help our deserving students afford their post high school education? post_text:
The Maritime Careers class took a tour of Prior Aviation today and we were able to introduce the cadets to jobs in the aviation industry.

The cadets got to go on a Lear Jet that was getting ready for a trip to Myrtle Beach and sit in the cockpit of a small single engine training plane. The general consensus was that they had a great time other than the cold.

Our tour guide was Richard Middaugh, the first Commandant of our fine institution. He is now the chief flight instructor at Prior Aviation.
